{
  "texts": [
    "MacIntyreFirst, practices and institutions; second, roles and biographies; third, traditions and political communities.properly navigating conflicts and the duty to help advance community traditions.",
    "As it ensures that no one is left behind, \"decent work\" aligns with the common good principle.",
    "We now examine how digitally transformed work can meet these criteria (Table 3).",
    "Moral valence depends on human purpose or intention and circumstances in which technology is used as well as the moral character of agents.Digital technology as a tool or instrument to increase efficiency at the service of flourishing.",
    "Collaboration with technology.Digital technology is an inevitable, natural force.Technological determinism (utopia or dystopia).Digital technology as a tool or instrument to increase efficiency for efficiency's sake.Competition with technology.DTW can be virtuous so long as it remains a human act that is productive and contributes to flourishing.DTW should be the product of a free, rational choice.Automate what is dull, dangerous, or dirty.Augment and enhance integral human agency.Decision or control outsourcing to machines (\"machine drift\"); treat humans as robots or robot appendages (\"algocracy\").Automate as much as possible (\"overautomation\").Impoverish human agency through exploitation and alienation (\"fauxtomation,\" \"so-so automation\").DTW should be supportive of the duty and right of individuals to work, regardless of socioeconomic status and other considerations.Quality job creation through proper human-computer interaction.Equitable distribution of the fruits of labor: inclusion.Technology-centric mind-set with humans as an afterthought (\"gap fillers\")."
  ]
}